intent: >
  Complete the walking skeleton by adding seed data that exercises both
  halves of the up/down policy. This commit is the "all code is in
  place" marker — the smoke test that follows is the verification gate.

slice: 8/8
kind: feature
behavior_change: additive

reversibility: trivial
# Seeds are data, not schema or code. Re-running with different data
# or deleting the rows is costless.

scope:
  declared:
    - db/seeds.rb
  actual:
    - db/seeds.rb
  drift: []

proof:
  tests_run: bin/dc bundle exec rspec
  result: green
  failing: 0

tests:
  needed: "no"
  rationale: >
    Seeds are a data fixture for the manual smoke test, not a code path
    that needs automated verification. The smoke test itself (described
    in the commit message and the plan's verification section) is the
    test. The seed file is 11 lines of find_or_create_by! — if it
    raises, the error is self-evident.

assumptions:
  - "https://example.com returns 200 reliably — it is operated by IANA for exactly this purpose (RFC 2606). If it ever goes down, the seed will accurately demonstrate a transport error rather than a 200."
  - "https://example.com/definitely-not-a-real-page returns 404. If example.com's server ever starts returning 200 for all paths (wildcard routing), the 'always down' seed becomes an 'always up' seed and the smoke test still works — just both sides show green."
  - "find_or_create_by! is the right idempotency primitive. It matches on name (unique enough for seed data) and only sets url/interval_seconds on create, not on update. If you change the seed URL and re-run, the existing record keeps its old URL — acceptable for dev fixtures, not for production bootstrapping."

deviations_from_plan: none

trade_offs: >
  Seeds are deliberately minimal — two rows, no factories, no Faker.
  The smoke test only needs one healthy site and one unhealthy site to
  verify the full loop. More seeds would exercise more edge cases (e.g.,
  a site with a very short interval, a site with a transport error) but
  would not increase confidence in the walking skeleton's correctness.

self_review: {}

confidence: high

reviewer_attention: []
